'8:3': [
{sup:1, word:"not", lines:["The unjust ways of Samuel&rsquo;s sons were contrary to their father&rsquo;s pure and just way in his whole life ({1Sa12:3|12:3}-{1Sa12:5|5}) and gave the people of Israel cause to ask Samuel to appoint a king to judge them like all the nations (vv. {1Sa8:4|4}-{1Sa8:5|5}). Hence, the sons of Samuel should not be reckoned judges among the people of Israel ({Act13:20|Acts 13:20}), and their father Samuel should be considered the last judge.","The only defect in Samuel&rsquo;s history was that he appointed his two sons as judges among the children of Israel. Humanly, Samuel made a mistake in this matter, but this mistake helped God to manage the situation among His people by bringing in the kingship for the fulfillment of His economy."]},
{sup:"a", word:"gain", vrefs:"cf. Exo. 18:21"},
{sup:"b", word:"bribes", vrefs:"cf. Exo. 23:8; Deut. 16:19; Psa. 15:5"},
],
'8:5': [
{sup:"a", word:"king", vrefs:"cf. Deut. 17:14; 1&nbsp;Sam. 8:19-20; Hosea 13:10; Acts 13:21"},
{sup:1, word:"nations", lines:["Israel had been chosen by God to be a particular people on earth; therefore, they should have been absolutely different in every respect from the nations. Yet they took the way of following the nations by rejecting God as their King."]},
],
'8:7': [
{sup:"a", word:"not", vrefs:"cf. Exo. 16:8"},
{sup:"1b", word:"rejected", vrefs:"1&nbsp;Sam. 10:19", lines:["By insisting on having a king, the elect of God turned from God to a man. In doing this they not only displeased Samuel ({1Sa8:6|v. 6}) but also offended God by rejecting Him as their King and thus replacing Him ({1Sa8:7|v. 7}; {1Sa12:12|12:12}). This was a great wickedness, a great evil, in the sight of God ({1Sa12:17|12:17}, {1Sa12:19|19}). Whatever we may do, no matter how good, &ldquo;spiritual,&rdquo; and even scriptural it may be, it is evil in the sight of God if we reject Him as our Head, our Husband, and our King. It is not a matter of right or wrong; it is a matter of whether we take God as our King or reject Him. It is for this reason that Samuel as a Nazarite kept his hair long, covering his head with God Himself as his authority ({1Sa1:11|1:11}; {Num6:5|Num. 6:5})."]},
],
